data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime — with no opt-in to restore them.**

In EF Core 10 you could opt into sync-over-async for the Cosmos provider. **EF Core 11 removes that escape hatch entirely.** Every synchronous I/O API (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`, etc.) now **always throws**, regardless of configuration.

### What to fix

Convert every method to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

The mapping is:

| Sync (breaks in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |
| `Single()` | `await SingleAsync()` |
| `Any()` | `await AnyAsync()` |

This will ripple through your call chain — every caller of these repository methods will also need to become `async`. Remove the old sync-over-async opt-in configuration since it no longer has any effect.
